Here is a sample code showing an algorithm to check prime numbers in C++.

// Function to check prime numbers
bool isPrime(int n) 
{ 
    // Corner cases 
    if (n <= 1) 
        return false; 
    if (n <= 3) 
        return true; 

    // This is checked so that we can skip   
    // middle five numbers in below loop 
    if (n % 2 == 0 || n % 3 == 0) 
        return false; 

    for (int i = 5; i * i <= n; i = i + 6) 
        if (n % i == 0 || n % (i + 2) == 0) 
            return false; 

    return true; 
} 

The above code is a simple implementation of the sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm, which works by looping through all the numbers from 2 to the input number and checking if each of those numbers is divisible by any of the preceding numbers. If not, then the number is considered to be prime.

